Curves in the plane
	- Tangent and Normal vector
		- Assume: The curve itself: a(s) = (x(s), y(s))
		- Calc: The tangent vector of the curve
		- Def: The normal Vector of the curve
			- Note: There are two possible ways to determine a normal vector.
			- Define normal vector st {T, N} is orthonormal and positevely oriented.
		- Calc: {T, N} vectors are orthonormal and positively oriented.
	- Signed curvature
		- Def: Signed curvature of the curve.
		- Note: Difference in between positive and negative curvatures.
		- Calc: Module of the curvature (in function of x'' and y'')
		- Calc: Curvature (in function of x',y',x'',y''.
		- Def: Radius of curvature.
	- Curve under general parameter (instead of arc length)
		- ASsume: The curve itself: a(t) = (x(t), y(t)).
		- Calc: The tangent vector
		- Calc: The Normal Vector
		- Calc: The signed curvature
		- Calc: The module of curvature
	- Examples: line, circle, parabola, elipse, hyperbola
		- Calc: Tangent Vector
		- Calc: Normal Vector
		- Calc: Signed Curvature
	- Derivative of Normal Vector
		- Recall: T'(s) = k(s) N(s)
		- Calc: N'(s).
		- Show: <N'(s), T(s)> = -k
		- Then: N'(s) = -k(s) T(s)
	- Frenet Equations
		- The two frenet equations for curves in the plane
		- Frenet equations in matrix form.
	- Examples:
		- Calc: Show all plane curves with zero curvature are lines
		- Calc: Show all plane curves with cte curvature are circles
		- Calc: Show all plane curves with 1/(as+b) curvature are logarithmic spirals.
	- Fundamental Theorem of the Curves in the plane.
		- Theorem: There exists an unique curve continuously differentiable arc length parameterized I --> R^2 st:
			- Curvature is given by continuous function k: I --> R.
			- Initial point is specified: a(s0)= p
			- Initial tangent is specified: vector a'(s0) = v.
		- Proof of the theorem
			- Step 01: Use First Frenet Equation. Arrive at two coupled second order linear ODE.
			- Step 02: Theorem of Existance and unicity of linear ODE: There is unique continuously differentiable solution with IVP.
			- Step 03: Find the solution of the ODE with specified by IVP.
		- Calc: Find tangent vector of the solution
		- Calc: Show solution curve is unitary, and hence arc length parameterized.
		- Calc: Find normal vector of the solution.
		- Calc: Find signed curvature of the solution.
		- Note: This tells curvature is an instrinsic properties of curves.
		- Note: Now we have a way of calculating any curve only from it curvature. =).
		- Example: Calculate for 0 curvature, and cte curvature, using this.



